SECTION 2: TOOL INTEGRATION AND FUNCTION CALLING (Exam Obj 2.3)
================================================================================

---------------------------------------
2.1 What Tools Are and Why They Matter
---------------------------------------
Tools are the bridge between the LLM's reasoning and the real world.
Without tools, an agent can only use its training data.
With tools, an agent can: search the web, query databases, send emails,
  check system status, calculate values, read files, call APIs.

Tool categories:
  SEARCH: Web search, document search, vector store search
  COMPUTATION: Calculator, code execution, data analysis
  DATA ACCESS: Database queries, API calls, file reading
  ACTIONS: Send email, create ticket, update record, trigger workflow
  MULTIMODAL: Image analysis (vision), speech-to-text, OCR

---------------------------------------
2.2 Tool Definition Requirements — Critical for Exam
---------------------------------------
A tool needs three things:
  1. name: Unique identifier the LLM uses to call it
  2. description: Natural language explanation — THIS IS CRITICAL
  3. func: The actual Python function to execute

THE DESCRIPTION IS THE MOST IMPORTANT PART.
The LLM decides WHEN to use a tool based solely on its description.
A vague description = wrong tool selection = wrong answers.

GOOD DESCRIPTION TEMPLATE:
  - What the tool does (one sentence)
  - When to use it (context/trigger)
  - What the input should be (format, constraints)
  - What it returns (so agent knows what to do with it)
  - What NOT to use it for (prevents misuse)

EXAMPLE:
  BAD: description="Search for information"
  GOOD: description="""Search internal documentation for technical answers.
    Use when the user asks about product features, configuration, or troubleshooting.
    Input should be a specific search query (3-10 words).
    Returns: relevant doc excerpts.
    Do NOT use for real-time data, pricing, or external news."""

---------------------------------------
2.3 Pydantic Input Validation for Tools
---------------------------------------
Use Pydantic BaseModel as args_schema for structured validation:

  class ToolInput(BaseModel):
    query: str = Field(min_length=3, max_length=200)
    filters: Optional[List[str]] = None

Benefits:
  - Input is validated BEFORE tool executes (fail fast)
  - Clear schema documentation in tool definition
  - LLM can see field descriptions for better tool calling
  - Type errors caught at schema validation, not deep in tool logic

---------------------------------------
2.4 API Integration Best Practices
---------------------------------------
Robust API tool implementation must handle:

TIMEOUT: Always set timeout parameter. Network calls can hang indefinitely.
  Default timeout = 5-10 seconds. Never leave default (None).

HTTP STATUS CODES TO HANDLE:
  200: Success
  400: Bad request — don't retry (your fault)
  401/403: Auth error — don't retry (fix credentials)
  404: Not found — don't retry (resource doesn't exist)
  429: Rate limited — retry with backoff (too many requests)
  500/502/503: Server error — retry with backoff (their fault, transient)
  504: Gateway timeout — retry with backoff

EXPONENTIAL BACKOFF PATTERN:
  delay = initial_delay * (backoff_factor ^ attempt_number)
  Attempt 0: delay = 1s * (2^0) = 1s
  Attempt 1: delay = 1s * (2^1) = 2s
  Attempt 2: delay = 1s * (2^2) = 4s
  Max attempts: 3 is typical. Total wait: 1+2+4 = 7s.

  KEY RULE: Only retry on 5xx and 429. Never retry on 4xx (except 429).

---------------------------------------
2.5 Multimodal Tools — NVIDIA Vision
---------------------------------------
NVIDIA model for vision: microsoft/phi-3-vision-128k-instruct
  (or other NVIDIA vision models available via API)

Pattern for image analysis:
  1. Load image file → base64 encode
  2. Build multimodal message: [{type: text, text: question},
     {type: image_url, image_url: {url: data:image/jpeg;base64,...}}]
  3. Send to vision LLM via ChatNVIDIA
  4. Return response.content

Use cases for vision tools in agents:
  - Screenshot analysis (error detection from UI screenshots)
  - Document OCR (extract text from scanned docs)
  - Image classification (product categorization, defect detection)
  - Chart/graph reading (extract data from visual reports)


