SECTION 3: ERROR HANDLING AND RESILIENCE (Exam Obj 2.4)
================================================================================

---------------------------------------
3.1 The Three Resilience Patterns — Must Know All Three
---------------------------------------

PATTERN 1: RETRY WITH EXPONENTIAL BACKOFF
  Problem it solves: Transient failures — temporary network blips, brief
    service overload, occasional 503s that recover within seconds.
  How it works: Retry the same call N times with increasing delay between.
  Config: max_retries=3, initial_delay=1s, backoff_factor=2.0
  When NOT to use: 4xx errors (except 429) — retrying won't fix bad requests.
  Total max wait time with 3 retries: 1+2+4 = 7 seconds.

PATTERN 2: CIRCUIT BREAKER
  Problem it solves: Cascading failures — when a downstream service is down
    for minutes/hours and you don't want your agent to keep hammering it
    (wasting resources and piling up timeouts).
  Three states:
    CLOSED: Normal operation. All requests pass through.
    OPEN: Failure threshold exceeded (e.g., 5 consecutive failures).
      ALL requests immediately rejected. Service not called at all.
    HALF_OPEN: After timeout period (e.g., 60s), allow ONE test request.
      If success → CLOSED. If failure → back to OPEN.
  When to use: Long-running outages, prevent resource exhaustion, cascade protection.
  
  CLOSED → OPEN: When failure_count >= failure_threshold
  OPEN → HALF_OPEN: When (now - last_failure_time) > timeout
  HALF_OPEN → CLOSED: Successful test request
  HALF_OPEN → OPEN: Failed test request

PATTERN 3: GRACEFUL DEGRADATION
  Problem it solves: When primary capability fails, provide reduced but
    still useful functionality rather than hard crash.
  How it works: Tier of fallbacks:
    1. Try primary (70B model via NIM)
    2. If fails → fallback (8B model, smaller, more available)
    3. If fails → cached response (stale but better than nothing)
    4. If fails → rule-based response ("I'm experiencing issues...")
  When to use: Production systems that must never return an error page.
    User experience > perfect accuracy.

CHOOSING BETWEEN THEM:
  Transient, seconds-level failures → Retry with backoff
  Minutes-level outages, cascade risk → Circuit Breaker
  Capability degradation, fallback scenarios → Graceful Degradation
  In reality: Use all three together. They're complementary, not alternatives.

---------------------------------------
3.2 Timeout Management
---------------------------------------
Every external call MUST have a timeout.

LAYER 1: HTTP timeout — max time for a single HTTP request (e.g., 5-10s)
LAYER 2: Agent execution timeout — max time for entire agent loop (e.g., 30s)
LAYER 3: Tool-level timeout — max time for a specific tool call

AgentExecutor parameters:
  max_execution_time=30  → entire agent run limited to 30 seconds
  max_iterations=10      → maximum ReAct loop iterations

For Python-level timeout: use signal.alarm (Unix) or
  concurrent.futures with future.result(timeout=N)

---------------------------------------
3.3 Common Failure Scenarios in Exam
---------------------------------------

"API fails 10% of time with 503, recovers in 5 seconds, user expects <10s"
→ Retry with exponential backoff (1s + 2s = 3s wait) = well within 10s budget

"Service is down for 30+ minutes, agent keeps timing out"
→ Circuit Breaker — after N failures, stop calling, save resources

"Primary 70B model endpoint unavailable, users need responses"
→ Graceful degradation — fall back to 8B model or cached responses

"Tool input comes from user and may be malformed"
→ Pydantic validation + try/catch + specific error messages


