SECTION 4: NVIDIA NIM AND TENSORRT-LLM (Exam Obj 2.5)
================================================================================

---------------------------------------
4.1 NIM — What It Is and Why It Matters
---------------------------------------
NIM = NVIDIA Inference Microservices.
Pre-packaged, optimized, containerized LLM deployment.

What NIM gives you over naive model deployment:
  - TensorRT-LLM optimization (2-8x faster inference)
  - Automatic request batching (dramatically increases throughput)
  - KV cache management (reuse attention computation for efficiency)
  - Multi-GPU tensor parallelism (scale beyond single GPU)
  - Health check endpoints (/v1/health)
  - OpenAI-compatible API (drop-in replacement)
  - Load balancing across instances

Performance comparison:
  Standard PyTorch:      ~2000ms latency,  ~10 req/s
  TensorRT-LLM FP16:     ~500ms latency,   ~40 req/s
  TensorRT-LLM INT8:     ~250ms latency,   ~80 req/s
  NIM (TRT + batching):  ~200ms latency,   ~100+ req/s

Self-hosted NIM:
  docker pull nvcr.io/nim/meta/llama-3.1-70b-instruct:latest
  docker run --gpus all -p 8000:8000 -e NGC_API_KEY=... [container]
  Then: ChatNVIDIA(base_url="http://localhost:8000/v1", model="...")

Cloud NIM (NVIDIA AI Endpoints):
  ChatNVIDIA(base_url="https://integrate.api.nvidia.com/v1", nvidia_api_key="...")

---------------------------------------
4.2 TensorRT-LLM Optimizations — Know These
---------------------------------------

KERNEL FUSION: Combines multiple GPU operations into one.
  Less GPU overhead, higher throughput.

QUANTIZATION: Reduce numerical precision.
  FP32 → FP16: 2x memory reduction, minimal accuracy loss (default)
  FP16 → INT8: 2x further reduction, small accuracy loss
  INT8 → INT4: 2x further reduction, noticeable accuracy loss
  Use case: INT8 for production throughput. INT4 only if memory-constrained.

IN-FLIGHT BATCHING: Process multiple requests simultaneously during generation.
  Traditional: Wait for one request to finish before starting next.
  In-flight: Interleave multiple requests at token level. ~4x throughput gain.

KV CACHE: Reuse key/value computations for common prefixes.
  If many users send similar system prompts, compute once, reuse many times.
  enable_prefix_caching: True in NIM config.

TENSOR PARALLELISM: Split model across multiple GPUs.
  tensor_parallel_size=4 → split across 4 GPUs.
  Enables 70B model on 4x A100s vs requiring single 8x GPU machine.

---------------------------------------
4.3 Streaming Responses
---------------------------------------
Streaming = send tokens to client as they're generated, not waiting for
full response before sending anything.

Why it matters for UX:
  Without streaming: User stares at blank screen for 3 seconds, then sees answer.
  With streaming: User sees answer appearing word by word immediately.
  Perceived latency = time to first token (TTFT), not total generation time.
  TTFT with streaming: <200ms. Without: 3-5s. 15-25x perceived improvement.

Implementation: streaming=True on ChatNVIDIA + callbacks or .stream() method.

Callback events to handle:
  on_llm_new_token: Each token as it's generated (update UI)
  on_llm_end: Generation complete (finalize UI state)
  on_llm_error: Error occurred (show error state)
  on_agent_action: Agent is using a tool (show "thinking" indicator)

Production streaming pattern:
  Show "Agent is searching..." when tool called (on_agent_action)
  Stream token by token to UI (on_llm_new_token)
  Show "✓ Complete" on finish (on_llm_end)
  Never show raw stack traces in streaming errors

---------------------------------------
4.4 Model Selection Strategy
---------------------------------------
NVIDIA models available via API (key exam examples):
  meta/llama-3.1-8b-instruct: Fast, cheap, simple tasks
  meta/llama-3.1-70b-instruct: Powerful, general-purpose, complex tasks
  microsoft/phi-3-vision-128k-instruct: Vision/multimodal tasks

ROUTING STRATEGY:
  Short query (<20 words), simple question → 8B model
  Complex reasoning, multi-step, analysis → 70B model
  Contains image reference → vision model
  Implement as pre-classification step using 8B model to classify → route


