SECTION 5: CONVERSATION FLOWS AND STATE (Exam Obj 2.5)
================================================================================

---------------------------------------
5.1 Conversation Memory Types (LangChain)
---------------------------------------

ConversationBufferMemory:
  Keeps ALL messages. Simple but grows unboundedly.
  Use for: Short sessions where all history matters.

ConversationBufferWindowMemory(k=N):
  Keeps last N message pairs. Bounded memory.
  Use for: Most conversational agents. k=10 is reasonable default.

ConversationSummaryMemory:
  Summarizes old messages, keeps recent ones.
  Requires an LLM call to summarize.
  Use for: Long conversations where early context still matters.

ConversationSummaryBufferMemory:
  Hybrid: Keep recent messages as-is, summarize older ones.
  Best of both. Most sophisticated but most complex.

---------------------------------------
5.2 Context-Aware Routing
---------------------------------------
Pattern: Analyze conversation context → classify intent → route to handler.

Steps:
  1. Classify intent from recent messages (use small fast model)
  2. Detect sentiment (positive/neutral/negative)
  3. Count turns (long conversation = different handling)
  4. Route to specialized handler based on classification

Key routing signals:
  ESCALATION: Negative sentiment + unresolved issue + N turns
  TECHNICAL: Technical terms, error codes, specific product questions
  BILLING: Dollar amounts, account numbers, payment questions
  GENERAL: Anything else

---------------------------------------
5.3 Adaptive Response Generation
---------------------------------------
Adapt responses based on user profile/preferences:
  verbosity: low (1-2 sentences), medium (balanced), high (detailed)
  technical_level: beginner (no jargon), intermediate, expert
  format: conversational, formal, concise (bullet points)

Store preferences in user profile, update based on feedback signals:
  "Too long" → reduce verbosity
  "More detail" → increase verbosity
  "Too technical" → reduce technical_level
  "I'm an expert" → increase technical_level


